"title": "5225: barrenness",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "5225: barrenness",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>A lack of fertility, especially the inability of a woman to conceive.</p>\n<h2>Barren land</h2>\n<h3>Barrenness describes waste and unproductive land</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer2:6\">JER 2:6</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut32:10\">DEU 32:10</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Joel2:20\">JOL 2:20</a></p>\n<h3>Barren land as a sign of God's disfavour</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen3:18\">GEN 3:18</a></strong> <em>Thorns and thistles are often used to designate barren or unproductive land.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Hos10:8\">HOS 10:8</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb6:8\">HEB 6:8</a></p>\n<h2>Fertility, as opposed to barrenness, a sign of God's blessing</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod23:25-Exod23:26\">EXO 23:25–23:26</a></strong> <em>Consequently, the inability to conceive was regarded as a sign of God's displeasure.</em> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut7:13-Deut7:14\">DEU 7:13–7:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut11:14-Deut11:15\">DEU 11:14–11:15</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps113:9\">PSA 113:9</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa41:18\">ISA 41:18</a>ISA <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa54:1\">54:1</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gal4:27\">GAL 4:27</a></p>\n<h2>The barren woman</h2>\n<h3>Her desire for children</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen30:1-Gen30:2\">GEN 30:1–30:2</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Prov30:16\">PRO 30:16</a></p>\n<h3>Examples of barren women</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen16:1\">GEN 16:1</a> <em>Sarah</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:31\">GEN 29:31</a> <em>Rachel</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg13:3\">JDG 13:3</a> <em>Manoah's wife</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam2:5\">1SA 2:5</a> <em>Hannah</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:7\">LUK 1:7</a> <em>Elizabeth</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:36-Luke1:37\">LUK 1:36–1:37</a> <em>The ability to bear a child in these circumstances, especially in old age, was seen as a sign of God's blessing and his miraculous power.</em></p>\n<h3>Barrenness was sometimes seen as a sign of God's disfavour</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen16:1-Gen16:4\">GEN 16:1–16:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen20:17-Gen20:18\">GEN 20:17–20:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen29:31-Gen29:34\">GEN 29:31–29:34</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Sam1:1-1Sam1:20\">1SA 1:1–1:20</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Isa4:1\">ISA 4:1</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke1:5-Luke1:25\">LUK 1:5–1:25</a></p>\n<h3>Childlessness was not always the result of barrenness</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut28:41\">DEU 28:41</a></strong></p>\n<h3>Barrenness might be an advantage in some circumstances</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke23:29\">LUK 23:29</a></strong> <em>Referring to the disasters about to come upon Jerusalem.</em></p>\n<h2>Metaphorically, barrenness may describe an unproductive or desperate condition</h2>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb6:7-Heb6:8\">HEB 6:7–6:8</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job3:7\">JOB 3:7</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke13:6-Luke13:9\">LUK 13:6–13:9</a></p>",
